.zonai.com/promociones/biografias/0101/josecampeche.asp |accessdate=7 October 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110927074034/http://www.zonai.com/promociones/biografias/0101/josecampeche.asp |archivedate=27 September 2011 }}</ref>\n}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Writers from Puerto Rico}}\n*Acosta-Bel\u00e9n, Edna. \"Puerto Rican Literature in the United States,\" in ''Redefining American Literary History'', Ed. A. LaVonne Brown Ruoff and Jerry W. Ward, MLA, 1990.\n*Aldama, Frederick. ''Routledge Concise History of Latino/a Literature,'' featuring Puerto Rican authors Miguel Algar\u00edn, Giannina Braschi, Pedro Pietri, Miguel Pi\u00f1ero, Esmeralda Santiago, Piri Thomas, et al., Routledge, 2013.\n*''[http://www1.uprh.edu/zjimenez/GENERACION80/bibliografia.htm Bibliograf\u00eda de escritores puertorrique\u00f1os de la Generaci\u00f3n Ochenta (Generation of the 80's)]''.\n*Cancel, Mario R. ''Literatura y narrativa puertorrique\u00f1a: la escritura entre siglos''. San Juan: Pasadizo, 2007.\n*Callahan, Laura. ''Spanish/English Codeswitching in a Written Corpus.'' John Benjamins Publishing, 2004. \n*Castillo, Debra. ''Redreaming America: Toward a Bilingual American Culture.'' On Ana Lydia Vega and Giannina Braschi. SUNY Series in Latin American and Iberian Thought and Culture, 2005. \n*L\u00f3pez Baralt, Mercedes. ''Literatura Puertorrique\u00f1a del Siglo XX:  Antolog\u00eda''. San Juan: EDUPR, 2004.\n*Mart\u00ednez M\u00e1rquez, Alberto, and Mario Cancel. ''El l\u00edmite volcado.  Antolog\u00eda de la Generaci\u00f3n de Poetas de los Ochenta''.  San Juan:  Isla Negra, 2000.\n* Milligan, Bryce, ''Floricanto S\u00ed!: A Collection of Latina Poetry.'' Penguin, 1998.\n*Moreira, Rub\u00e9n Alejandro. ''Antolog\u00eda de la poes\u00eda puertorrique\u00f1a. Vol. I Romanticismo; Vol.II Modernismo y Postmodernismo; Vol. III Contempor\u00e1nea; Vol. IV Contempor\u00e1nea''. San Juan: Tr\u00edptico, 1992-1993.\n*Ortega, Julio. ''Antolog\u00eda de la poes\u00eda latinoamericana del siglo XXI: el turno y la transici\u00f3n''. M\u00e9xico: Editorial Siglo XXI, 1997.\n*Torres, Lourdes. \"In the Contact Zone: Code-Switching Strategies by Latino/a Writers\", JUSTOR, 2007.\n*Stanchich, Maritza. \"Insular Interventions: Diasporic Puerto Rican Literature Bilanguaging toward a Greater Puerto Rico.\" Ph.D. diss, University of California, Santa Cruz, 2003.\n*Torres-Padilla, Jos\u00e9 L. and Carmen Hayd\u00e9e Rivera. ''Writing Off the Hyphen: New Critical Perspectives on the Literature of the Puerto Rican Diaspora.'' University of Washington Press, 2008. \n*Williams, Raymond L. ''The Columbia Guide to the Latin American Novel Since 1945.'' Featuring Puerto Rican novelists Giannina Braschi, Edgardo Rodr\u00edguez Juli\u00e1, Luis Rafael Sanchez, and Esmeralda Santiago. New york: Columbia University Press, 2007.\n*Zimmerman, Marc. ''U.S. Latino Literature: An Essay and Annotated Bibliography.'' MARCH/Abrazo, 1992.\n\n{{Lists of writers by nationality}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:List Of Puerto Rican Writers}}\n[[Category:Puerto Rican writers| List]]\n[[Category:Lists of Puerto Rican people by occupation|Writers]]\n[[Category:Lists of writers by nationality|Puerto Rican]]\n[[Category:Hispanic and Latino American writers| List]]\n[[Category:Lists of American writers|Puerto]]\n", "name_user": "Lawrlafo", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eT-Z:Added middle initial to Iris M. Zavala", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_Puerto_Rican_writers"}
{"title_page": "Sonia Ahmed", "text_new": "{{Infobox person\n| name        = Sonia Ahmed\n| image       = Sonia ahmed.jpg\n| image_size  = 100px\n| caption     = \n| birth_name  = Sonia Iqbal Ahmed\n| birth_date  = {{birth date and age|df=yes|1980|08|23}}\n| yearsactive = 2003-present\n| birth_place = [[Sharq, Kuwait]]\n| known_for   = Creating Pakistan's Pageant Industry [[Miss Pakistan World]] [[Mrs. Pakistan World]]\n| residence = [[Toronto, Ontario]], Canada\n| death_date  =\n| death_place =\n| education = [[University of Ottawa]] [[Bachelor of Business]]\n| occupation  = [[President (corporate title)|President]], [[Miss Pakistan World]] [[Mrs. Pakistan World]] Mr. Pakistan World\n| website     = [http://www.soniaahmedofficial.com/ Official Sonia Ahmed Site]\n}} {{Commons}}\n\n'''Sonia Ahmed''' ([[Punjabi language|Punjabi]]/[[Urdu]]: \u0633\u0648\u0646\u06cc\u0627 \u0627\u062d\u0645\u062f)] (born 23 August 1980), is a Kuwaiti born Pakistani and founder of Miss Canada Pakistan Inc., also known as [[Miss Pakistan World]],<ref name = \"nytimes\">{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2008/12/19/nyregion/19bigcity.html|title=Pakistan May Not Be Ready For Its Beauty Queen|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|accessdate=15 November 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"ryerson\">{{cite web|url=http://www.diversitywatch.ryerson.ca/media/cache/pakistanipageant_star_mar14.htm|title=DIVERSITY WATCH - Media - 2003 Archive|publisher=Diversitywatch.ryerson.ca|access-date=15 November 2014|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110606012613/http://www.diversitywatch.ryerson.ca/media/cache/pakistanipageant_star_mar14.htm|archive-date=6 June 2011|df=}}</ref> Mr. Pakistan World and [[Mrs. Pakistan World]].<ref>https://www.thestar.com/news/gta/2010/01/14/porter_this_beauty_queen_has_brains_and_bite.html</ref> She is a pioneer in the international beauty and talent pageant industry for Pakistan. Ahmed started the pageant industry for Pakistan in 2002 in [[Toronto, Ontario]], Canada.<ref name = \"nytimes\"/>\n\n==Biography==\n\n===Early life===\nSonia Ahmed was born in Pakistan. She spent her childhood in [[Kuwait]], [[Karachi]], Canada. Ahmed <ref name=\"ryerson\"/> attended [[Carmel School (Kuwait)]] convent in [[Kuwait]] after which her family moved to [[Ottawa]] in Canada, where she attended [[Notre Dame High School (Ottawa)|Notre Dame Catholic High School]]. Always an academic, Ahmed was awarded a medal for being ranked in the top 15 academically at her high school in Canada and also received a $8,000 scholarship to attend the [[University of Ottawa]] where she earned a degree in Business. Ahmed continued in CGA<ref name=\"indianexpress.com\">{{cite web|url=http://www.indianexpress.com/news/pakistani-beauty-pageant-aims-to-celebrate-womanhood/884115/|title=Pakistani beauty pageant aims to celebrate womanhood|publisher=Indianexpress.com|accessdate=15 November 2014}}</ref> (Certified General Accounting) up to the 4th level and then left it to pursue the pageant as full-fledged business in entertainment. Ahmed, grew up in [[Kuwait]] and learnt many languages which included written & spoken [[Hindi]], [[Arabic]], [[Urdu]] & [[French language|French]] besides English.\n\n==Career==\n\n===Founder of Pakistan's pageant industry===\nAhmed was the first person to established a [[Beauty pageant|pageant]] industry for [[Pakistan]]. She created all three pageants<ref>https://beautypageants.indiatimes.com/Everything-you-need-to-know-about-Miss-Pakistan-World/Everything-you-need-to-know-about-Miss-Pakistan-World/eventshow/58239381.cms</ref> and gave a strong structure to all competitions.<ref>https://uk.blastingnews.com/showbiz-tv/2017/03/pakistani-muslim-girl-ramina-ashfaque-takes-part-in-miss-earth-contest-in-bikini-001521041.html</ref> Living in [[Toronto]], [[Ontario]], Ahmed<ref>{{cite web|url=http://tribune.com.pk/story/127030/miss-pakistan-world/|title=Miss Pakistan World|publisher=Tribune.com.pk|accessdate=15 November 2014}}</ref> considers herself a driving force for the \"progression\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.zeenews.com/news642066.html|title=Pak beauty pageant organiser sick of hypocrite Pakistanis|work=Zee News|accessdate=15 November 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mid-day.com/news/2009/feb/180209-Pakistani-beauty-queen-opposes-deal-on-Shariah-law.htm|title=Pakistani beauty queen opposes deal on Shariah law|publisher=Mid-day.com|accessdate=15 November 2014}}</ref> and \"liberation\" <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.siliconindia.com/shownews/Stop_Sharia_laws_kick_out_Taliban_nomads_Miss_Pakistan_World-nid-52643.html|title=Stop Sharia laws, kick out Taliban nomads: Miss Pakistan World|author=IANS|work=siliconindia|accessdate=15 November 2014}}</ref> of Pakistani women on a global scale.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.theasiantoday.com/article.aspx?articleId=176|title=Crowning glory for 'Miss Pakistan' beauty pageants|publisher=Theasaintoday.com|access-date=15 November 2014|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141129041140/http://www.theasiantoday.com/article.aspx?articleId=176|archive-date=29 November 2014|df=}}</ref> Working through her pageants, Ahmed aims to build cultural connections to showcase the beauty and talent of what she considers a new Pakistani generation.<ref name=\"khaleejtimes.com\">{{cite web|url=http://www.khaleejtimes.com/citytimes/inside.asp?xfile=/data/citytimes/2009/August/citytimes_August240.xml&section=citytimes|title=Celeb talk: The world at her fingertips|publisher=Khaleejtimes.com\\Accessdate=15 November 2014}}</ref>\n\n===Miss Pakistan World===\nIn 2002, Ahmed had announced the first pageant for Pakistan in the world, called Miss Canada Pakistan, and for three years Ahmed continued the pageant in Canada for Pakistani girls residing in Canada only. In 2006, Ahmed changed the pageant name to Miss Pakistan World, and carried on the pageant internationally and hence established the first official pageant for Pakistan. Ahmed consider's these events as a sort of civil rights<ref name=\"indianexpress.com\"/> movements,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dnaindia.com/world/report_pakistani-canadian-kills-daughter-over-hijab_1138800|title=Pakistani Canadian kills daughter over hijab|work=dna|accessdate=15 November 2014}}</ref><ref>[http://www.dailymailnews.com/0908/20/ShowBiz/ShowBiz1.php]  {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091209190509/http://www.dailymailnews.com/0908/20/ShowBiz/ShowBiz1.php |date=December 9, 2009 }}</ref> through which it is hoped that the young and married women of Pakistan are able to gain a voice on the international stage.<ref name=\"tribuneindia.com\">{{cite web|url=http://www.tribuneindia.com/2011/20111205/ttlife1.htm|title=The Tribune, Chandigarh, India - The Tribune Lifestyle|publisher=Tribuneindia.com|accessdate=15 November 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.desixpress.co.uk/article.aspx?articleId=176|title=Desixpress.co.uk - No .1 For Asian Entertainment|publisher=Tribuneindia.com|accessdate=15 November 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141129025316/http://www.desixpress.co.uk/article.aspx?articleId=176|archive-date=29 November 2014|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n===Mrs. Pakistan World===\nIn 2007, Ahmed established the Mrs. Pakistan World<ref>[http://finance.alphatrade.com/story/2013-02-14/CNW/201302141718CANADANWCANADAPR_C5856.html] {{dead link|date=November 2014}}</ref> pageant for married Pakistani women from around the world. Winners were crowned from countries like USA, Canada and Norway. It was unimaginable for married Pakistani women to be seen in beauty pageants, and Ahmed made sure that married women<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.newswire.ca/en/story/1114989/pakistan-gets-its-mrs-pakistan-world-2013-farah-mahmood|title=Farah mahmood - Pakistan gets its Mrs. Pakistan World 2013 - Farah Mahmood|publisher=Newswire.ca|accessdate=15 November 2014}}</ref> of Pakistani descent were given an opportunity. Though the pageant was small, it did not go unnoticed, and took part in major international pageants like Mrs. World, [[Mrs. Universe]] and Mrs. Earth.\n\n===Mr. Pakistan World===\nIn 2011, Ahmed went ahead with the Mr. Pakistan World<ref>https://tribune.com.pk/story/1572317/4-pakistan-shines-mr-ocean-2017/</ref> event, a male competition for Pakistan to generate more youth to participate in areas where a lighter side of Pakistan could be shown.\n\nAfter the inclusion of the Mr. Pakistan World competition, the community participation increased with less resistance. [[Pakistan]]'s entertainment industry began changing as well and hence there was more stability in the acceptance of beauty pageants by Pakistan. This led to more scope for the competition out of Canada. In 2014, Ahmed moved the Miss Pakistan World and Mr. Pakistan World pageant to the United States<ref>{{cite web|url=http://thealternativepress.com/articles/2014-miss-pakistan-world-pageant-coming-to-edison|title=2014 Miss Pakistan World Pageant Coming to Edison|work=The Alternative Press|accessdate=15 November 2014}}</ref> and the 12th Miss Pakistan World and 4th Mr. Pakistan World took place in [[New Jersey]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.my9nj.com/story/26474107/2014-miss-pakistan-world-pageant-coming-to-edison |access-date=October 30, 2014 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141010080437/http://www.my9nj.com/story/26474107/2014-miss-pakistan-world-pageant-coming-to-edison |archive-date=October 10, 2014 }}</ref> USA. \n\n===Miss Pakistan===\nIn 2016, Ahmed got successful sending her first delegates directly from [[Pakistan]] to represent Pakistan in international pageants. Diya Ali<ref>https://tribune.com.pk/story/1648074/4-lahore-based-diya-ali-participate-miss-eco-international-2018/</ref> was the first representative from Pakistan<ref>https://images.dawn.com/news/1176877</ref> in 2016, and won the Miss Perpetual<ref>http://tribune.com.pk/story/1281667/pakistani-model-aiming-miss-world-title/</ref> title in [[Manila]], [[Philippines]] at the [[Miss Asia Pacific International]] pageant.\n\n===Director/Producer===\nIn 2014, Ahmed filmed her first documentary, \"[[I Shall Dance]],<ref name=\"enewspak.com\">[https://archive.is/20140707112313/http://enewspak.com/i-shall-dance-a-film-by-sonia-ahmed/]</ref><ref name=\"imdb.com\">{{cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt3776294|title=I Shall Dance (2014)|work=IMDb|accessdate=15 November 2014}}</ref>\" under her production company, Touchgate Global Inc., which released in September 2014{{Update after|2015|2|6}} in Toronto, Ontario, Canada.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://enewspak.com/i-shall-dance-a-documentary-on-dance-in-the-islamic-republic-of-pakistan/ |access-date=July 7, 2014 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140714213723/http://enewspak.com/i-shall-dance-a-documentary-on-dance-in-the-islamic-republic-of-pakistan/ |archive-date=July 14, 2014 }}</ref>\n\nIn 2016 Ahmed started her [[Lollywood]]<ref>http://images.dawn.com/news/1176095</ref> film production under her company Touchgate Global Inc. in Toronto, Ontario, Canada.<ref name=\"images.dawn.com\">http://images.dawn.com/news/1176154/mikaal-zulfiqar-and-ali-kazmi-to-star-in-a-desi-comedy-in-canada</ref> The name of the movie is \"[[Na Band Na Baraati]],\" starring [[Qavi Khan]], Azra Mohyeddin, [[Atiqa Odho]], [[Ali Kazmi]], [[Anzhelika Tahir]]<ref>https://tribune.com.pk/story/1302679/new-kids-block/</ref> and [[Mikaal Zulfiqar]] but has been unaccredited for it.\n\n==Filmography==\n{|class=\"wikitable\" style=\"font-size: 95%;\"\n|-\n! style=\"background:#B0C4DE;\" | Year\n! style=\"background:#B0C4DE;\" | Film\n! style=\"background:#B0C4DE;\" | Role\n! style=\"background:#B0C4DE;\" | Language\n! style=\"background:#B0C4DE;\" | Notes\n|-\n| 2020\n| ''TBA''\n|Director/Producer\n| Urdu\n|Filming \n|-\n| 2016\n| ''[[Na Band Na Baraati]]''<ref name=\"images.dawn.com\"/>\n|Director/Producer\n| Urdu\n|Unaccredited \n|-\n| 2014\n| ''[[I Shall Dance]]<ref name=\"enewspak.com\"/><ref name=\"imdb.com\"/>''\n|Director/Producer/Writer\n| Urdu/English\n|Ahmed's first documentary feature film\n|}\n\n==Other works==\nAhmed has been active part of charities around the world. In November 2011, Ahmed was invited to India,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://pakistanexaminer.com/?p=8784|title=HugeDomains.com - PakistanExaminer.com is for Sale (Pakistan Examiner)|publisher=Pakistanexaminer.com|accessdate=15 November 2014}}</ref> where she took part in various schools in regards to speaking<ref>{{cite web|url=http://solgens.us/india/bharatsandesh/newsdetail.php?n_id=712 |access-date=December 15, 2011 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120426052221/http://solgens.us/india/bharatsandesh/newsdetail.php?n_id=712 |archive-date=April 26, 2012 }}</ref> on India Pakistan relations<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tribuneindia.com/2011/20111209/cth1.htm#17|title=The Tribune, Chandigarh, India - Chandigarh Stories|publisher=Tribuneindia.com|accessdate=15 November 2014}}</ref> and on women's issues.<ref name=\"newseastwest.com\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.indianewscalling.com/tip.php?tipid=18124 |access-date=December 15, 2011 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120406072119/http://www.indianewscalling.com/tip.php?tipid=18124 |archive-date=April 6, 2012 }}</ref> Ahmed has also been an avid supporter of President [[Pervez Musharraf]] and has always shown her appreciation in the media.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.indianexpress.com/news/-i-love-you-musharraf-and-will-always-do-/523026/0|title=I love you Musharraf and will always do|publisher=Indianexpress.com|accessdate=15 November 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.southasianobserver.com/topstories.php?cid=1030|title=South Asian Observer - Top Story Indian Girl Wins Spelling Bee Contest In Ghana|publisher=Southasianobserver.com|access-date=15 November 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141128180005/http://www.southasianobserver.com/topstories.php?cid=1030|archive-date=2014-11-28|url-status=dead|df=}}</ref> Since 2012, Ahmed has started writing for publications in Canada<ref name=\"newseastwest.com\">{{cite web|url=http://newseastwest.com/why-india-and-pakistan-cannot-live-like-canada-and-us-and-call-themselves-hinpak-or-pakind-asks-miss-pakistan-world-boss-sonia-ahmed/|title=Why India and Pakistan cannot live like Canada and US, and call themselves 'HinPak' or 'Pakind,' asks Miss Pakistan World boss Sonia Ahmed|publisher=Newseastwest.com|access-date=15 November 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141129022744/http://newseastwest.com/why-india-and-pakistan-cannot-live-like-canada-and-us-and-call-themselves-hinpak-or-pakind-asks-miss-pakistan-world-boss-sonia-ahmed/|archive-date=2014-11-29|url-status=dead|df=}}</ref> and India<ref>{{cite web|url=http://newseastwest.com/miss-pakistan-pageant-founder-sonia-ahmed-on-why-musharraf-is-facing-all-these-problems-in-pakistan-today/|title=Miss Pakistan pageant founder Sonia Ahmed on why Musharraf is facing all these problems in Pakistan today|publisher=Newseastwest.com|accessdate=15 November 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://newseastwest.com/mistreatment-of-pakistani-artists-bothers-me/|title=Mistreatment of artists in Pakistan bothers me|publisher=Newseastwest.com|access-date=15 November 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141129022750/http://newseastwest.com/mistreatment-of-pakistani-artists-bothers-me/|archive-date=2014-11-29|url-status=dead|df=}}</ref>\n\n==Controversies==\n\nIn 2003,<ref name=\"Tehelka.com\">{{cite web|url=http://www.tehelka.com/story_main52.asp?filename=hub100312Neighbour.asp|title=Tehelka - India's Independent Weekly News Magazine|publisher=Tehelka.com|accessdate=15 November 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121014192605/http://www.tehelka.com/story_main52.asp?filename=hub100312Neighbour.asp|archive-date=14 October 2012|url-status=dead}}</ref> Ahmed<ref>http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/delhi-times/agents-of-change-or-miss-representations/articleshow/1973519.cms</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hindustantimes.com/Entertainment/Fashion/Miss-Pakistan-comes-to-India/Article1-803738.aspx|title=Miss Pakistan Comes To India|publisher=Hindustantimes.com|accessdate=15 November 2014}}</ref> was facing issues<ref name=\"tribuneindia.com\"/> with holding the pageant as some conservative sections<ref name=\"ryerson\"/> of the community were against the existence of Miss Pakistan World. As time went on, the controversies fizzled out.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.theasiantoday.com/article.aspx?articleId=176|title=Crowning glory for 'Miss Pakistan' beauty pageants|access-date=15 November 2014|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141129041140/http://www.theasiantoday.com/article.aspx?articleId=176|archive-date=29 November 2014|df=}}</ref> Moreover, Ahmed, was in the news several times expressing her likeness for the then President of Pakistan, [[Pervez Musharraf]].<ref>http://archive.indianexpress.com/news/-i-love-you-musharraf-and-will-always-do-/523026/</ref> Ahmed maintains that she is a hard core fan till to date.\n\nIn August 2010, Ahmed was criticized<ref name=\"Guardian\"/> for going ahead with the 8th annual Miss Pakistan World,<ref name= \"Guardian\">{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2010/aug/19/pakistan-anger-beauty-contest-floods|title=Miss Pakistan World pageant's timing causes dismay|work=the Guardian|accessdate=15 November 2014}}</ref><ref name= \"Toronto Star\">{{cite web|url=https://www.thestar.com/news/gta/article/850312--pakistani-beauty-pageant-to-go-ahead|title=Pakistani beauty pageant to go ahead|work=thestar.com|accessdate=15 November 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.care2.com/causes/human-rights/blog/is-a-miss-pakistan-pageant-appropriate-right-now/|title=Is a Miss Pakistan Pageant Appropriate Right Now?|publisher=Care2.com|accessdate=15 November 2014}}</ref> when Pakistan was hit with floods 3 weeks prior to the actual event.<ref name= \"Globe & Mail\">{{cite web|url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/news/national/toronto/organizers-criticized-for-running-pakistani-pageant-in-wake-of-flood-disaster/article1679280/|title=Organizers criticized for running Pakistani pageant in wake of flood disaster|work=The Globe and Mail|accessdate=15 November 2014}}</ref><ref>[http://www.torontosun.com/blogs/themotts/2010/08/23/15115626.html] {{dead link|date=November 2014}}</ref> Ahmed stood her grounds<ref name=\"Toronto Star\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://blogs.canoe.ca/themotts/disaster/few-flood-to-miss-pakistan/|title=Few Flood to Miss Pakistan|author=|work=The Motts Sound Off|access-date=15 November 2014|archive-url=https://archive.is/20120711224801/http://blogs.canoe.ca/themotts/disaster/few-flood-to-miss-pakistan/|archive-date=2012-07-11|url-status=dead|df=}}</ref> and said that the plans for holding the event would go on regardless. The other controversy surrounding the event was that it was held in the month of Ramadan. In an interview, Ahmed stated that the event was held after the fasting hours, and that Ramadan is a celebration not a mourning period. Ahmed has also always spoken very openly about her opponents who were mainly the conservative Pakistani community around the world.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://newseastwest.com/give-up-miss-pakistan-pageant-president-sonia-ahmed-tells-her-opponents/|archive-url=https://archive.is/20130130072314/http://newseastwest.com/give-up-miss-pakistan-pageant-president-sonia-ahmed-tells-her-opponents/|url-status=dead|archive-date=30 January 2013|title=Miss Pakistan World president Sonia Ahmed slams her opponents|publisher=Newseastwest.com|access-date=15 November 2014}}</ref> Ahmed<ref name=\"Tehelka.com\"/> has also backed controversial<ref>{{cite web|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/videos/celebs/Miss-Pak-World-president-backs-Veena-Malik/videoshow/11047751.cms |access-date=January 21, 2012 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120112114514/http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/videos/celebs/Miss-Pak-World-President-backs-Veena-Malik/videoshow/11047751.cms |archive-date=January 12, 2012 }}</ref> Pakistani actress [[Veena Malik]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.firstpost.com/printpage.php?idno=155625&sr_no=0|title=Print :Where's the fatwa? Veena Malik strips, Pakistan yawns|publisher=Firstpost.com|access-date=15 November 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150619234239/http://www.firstpost.com/printpage.php?idno=155625&sr_no=0|archive-date=2015-06-19|url-status=dead|df=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.indiablooms.com/EntVideo2Details/entPVVideoDetails091211l1.php|title=Miss Pak World prez backs Veena Malik|publisher=Indiablooms.com|access-date=15 November 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141109120850/http://www.indiablooms.com/EntVideo2Details/entPVVideoDetails091211l1.php|archive-date=2014-11-09|url-status=dead|df=}}</ref> on cover shoot for an Indian magazine FHM.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://video.in.msn.com/watch/video/miss-pak-world-prez-backs-veena/fdh5k7pk|title=Video - msn|publisher=Video.in.msn.com|accessdate=15 November 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120108123950/http://video.in.msn.com/watch/video/miss-pak-world-prez-backs-veena/fdh5k7pk|archive-date=8 January 2012|url-status=dead}}</ref> Ahmed also came on Indian live news channels, Tez Khabarain and [[Aaj Tak]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://aajtak.intoday.in/video/Veena-Malik-to-marry-on-TV-for-1.5-crore-1-686405.html|title=\u0935\u0940\u0928\u093e \u0915\u0947 \u0938\u094d\u200d\u0935\u092f\u0902\u0935\u0930 \u092a\u0930 \u0926\u094b \u0926\u0947\u0936\u094b\u0902 \u092e\u0947\u0902 \u092c\u0930\u092a\u093e \u0939\u0902\u0917\u093e\u092e\u093e \u0964 \u0939\u0938\u0940\u0928\u093e\u0913\u0902 \u0915\u093e \u091c\u0932\u0935\u093e \u0914\u0930 \u092d\u0940|publisher=Aajtak.intoday.in|accessdate=15 November 2014}}</ref> and defended Malik, against a local [[Mufti]], actress [[Dolly Bindra]] and actor [[Raza Murad]].\n\nOn December 5, 2019, Ahmed<ref>https://people.com/human-interest/former-miss-pakistan-world-zanib-naveed-dies-car-crash/</ref> was interviewed by [[People (magazine)]] [[Los Angeles]] [[United States]] for the untimely death of one of the winners of [[Miss Pakistan World]] [[Zanib Naveed]]. Ahmed answered, \u201cAs the President of Miss Pakistan World, we gave Naveed an amazing platform to represent Pakistan internationally and hearing about her death is very upsetting to all of us,\u201d Ahmed said. \u201cBeing a beauty queen to a country like Pakistan where there have been no beauty pageants on the soil of Pakistan is a tough job!\u201d \u201cNaveed along with other winners of Miss Pakistan World had a huge responsibility of carrying the title of a Muslim Nation,\u201d she continued. \u201cIt is a very upsetting time and terrible news and we can all hope and pray that her family gets through this painful situation.\u201d\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb name|6381973}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20120108123950/http://video.in.msn.com/watch/video/miss-pak-world-prez-backs-veena/fdh5k7pk ANI Interview]\n* [http://www.soniaahmedofficial.com/ Official Sonia Ahmed Site]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20110606012613/http://www.diversitywatch.ryerson.ca/media/cache/pakistanipageant_star_mar14.htm Toronto Star Article ]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Ahmed, Sonia}}\n[[Category:Canadian businesspeople of Pakistani descent]]\n[[Category:1980 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Pakistani Sunni Muslims]]\n[[Category:Pakistani women]]\n[[Category:Punjabi women]]\n[[Category:Businesspeople from Karachi]]\n[[Category:Businesspeople from Ottawa]]\n[[Category:Businesspeople from Toronto]]\n[[Category:Canadian people of Pakistani descent]]\n[[Category:Pakistani expatriates in Kuwait]]\n[[Category:University of Ottawa alumni]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox person\n| name        = Sonia Ahmed\n| image       = Sonia ahmed.jpg\n| image_size  = 100px\n| caption     = \n| birth_name  = Sonia Iqbal Ahmed\n| birth_date  = {{birth date and age|df=yes|1980|08|23}}\n| yearsactive = 2003-present\n| birth_place = [[Sharq, Kuwait]]\n| known_for   = Creating Pakistan's Pageant Industry [[Miss Pakistan World]] [[Mrs. Pakistan World]]\n| residence = [[Toronto, Ontario]], Canada\n| death_date  =\n| death_place =\n| education = [[University of Ottawa]] [[Bachelor of Business]]\n| occupation  = [[President (corporate title)|President]], [[Miss Pakistan World]] Mrs. Pakistan World Mr. Pakistan World\n| website     = [http://www.soniaahmedofficial.com/ Official Sonia Ahmed Site]\n}} {{Commons}}\n\n'''Sonia Ahmed''' ([[Punjabi language|Punjabi]]/[[Urdu]]: \u0633\u0648\u0646\u06cc\u0627 \u0627\u062d\u0645\u062f)] (born 23 August 1980), is a Kuwaiti born Pakistani and founder of Miss Canada Pakistan Inc., also known as [[Miss Pakistan World]],<ref name = \"nytimes\">{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2008/12/19/nyregion/19bigcity.html|title=Pakistan May Not Be Ready For Its Beauty Queen|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|accessdate=15 November 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"ryerson\">{{cite web|url=http://www.diversitywatch.ryerson.ca/media/cache/pakistanipageant_star_mar14.htm|title=DIVERSITY WATCH - Media - 2003 Archive|publisher=Diversitywatch.ryerson.ca|access-date=15 November 2014|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110606012613/http://www.diversitywatch.ryerson.ca/media/cache/pakistanipageant_star_mar14.htm|archive-date=6 June 2011|df=}}</ref> Mr. Pakistan World and [[Mrs. Pakistan World]].<ref>https://www.thestar.com/news/gta/2010/01/14/porter_this_beauty_queen_has_brains_and_bite.html</ref> She is a pioneer in the international beauty and talent pageant industry for Pakistan. Ahmed started the pageant industry for Pakistan in 2002 in [[Toronto, Ontario]], Canada.<ref name = \"nytimes\"/>\n\n==Biography==\n\n===Early life===\nSonia Ahmed was born in Pakistan. She spent her childhood in [[Kuwait]], [[Karachi]], Canada. Ahmed <ref name=\"ryerson\"/> attended [[Carmel School (Kuwait)]] convent in [[Kuwait]] after which her family moved to [[Ottawa]] in Canada, where she attended [[Notre Dame High School (Ottawa)|Notre Dame Catholic High School]]. Always an academic, Ahmed was awarded a medal for being ranked in the top 15 academically at her high school in Canada and also received a $8,000 scholarship to attend the [[University of Ottawa]] where she earned a degree in Business. Ahmed continued in CGA<ref name=\"indianexpress.com\">{{cite web|url=http://www.indianexpress.com/news/pakistani-beauty-pageant-aims-to-celebrate-womanhood/884115/|title=Pakistani beauty pageant aims to celebrate womanhood|publisher=Indianexpress.com|accessdate=15 November 2014}}</ref> (Certified General Accounting) up to the 4th level and then left it to pursue the pageant as full-fledged business in entertainment. Ahmed, grew up in [[Kuwait]] and learnt many languages which included written & spoken [[Hindi]], [[Arabic]], [[Urdu]] & [[French language|French]] besides English.\n\n==Career==\n\n===Founder of Pakistan's pageant industry===\nAhmed was the first person to established a [[Beauty pageant|pageant]] industry for [[Pakistan]]. She created all three pageants<ref>https://beautypageants.indiatimes.com/Everything-you-need-to-know-about-Miss-Pakistan-World/Everything-you-need-to-know-about-Miss-Pakistan-World/eventshow/58239381.cms</ref> and gave a strong structure to all competitions.<ref>https://uk.blastingnews.com/showbiz-tv/2017/03/pakistani-muslim-girl-ramina-ashfaque-takes-part-in-miss-earth-contest-in-bikini-001521041.html</ref> Living in [[Toronto]], [[Ontario]], Ahmed<ref>{{cite web|url=http://tribune.com.pk/story/127030/miss-pakistan-world/|title=Miss Pakistan World|publisher=Tribune.com.pk|accessdate=15 November 2014}}</ref> considers herself a driving force for the \"progression\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.zeenews.com/news642066.html|title=Pak beauty pageant organiser sick of hypocrite Pakistanis|work=Zee News|accessdate=15 November 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mid-day.com/news/2009/feb/180209-Pakistani-beauty-queen-opposes-deal-on-Shariah-law.htm|title=Pakistani beauty queen opposes deal on Shariah law|publisher=Mid-day.com|accessdate=15 November 2014}}</ref> and \"liberation\" <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.siliconindia.com/shownews/Stop_Sharia_laws_kick_out_Taliban_nomads_Miss_Pakistan_World-nid-52643.html|title=Stop Sharia laws, kick out Taliban nomads: Miss Pakistan World|author=IANS|work=siliconindia|accessdate=15 November 2014}}</ref> of Pakistani women on a global scale.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.theasiantoday.com/article.aspx?articleId=176|title=Crowning glory for 'Miss Pakistan' beauty pageants|publisher=Theasaintoday.com|access-date=15 November 2014|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141129041140/http://www.theasiantoday.com/article.aspx?articleId=176|archive-date=29 November 2014|df=}}</ref> Working through her pageants, Ahmed aims to build cultural connections to showcase the beauty and talent of what she considers a new Pakistani generation.<ref name=\"khaleejtimes.com\">{{cite web|url=http://www.khaleejtimes.com/citytimes/inside.asp?xfile=/data/citytimes/2009/August/citytimes_August240.xml&section=citytimes|title=Celeb talk: The world at her fingertips|publisher=Khaleejtimes.com\\Accessdate=15 November 2014}}</ref>\n\n===Miss Pakistan World===\nIn 2002, Ahmed had announced the first pageant for Pakistan in the world, called Miss Canada Pakistan, and for three years Ahmed continued the pageant in Canada for Pakistani girls residing in Canada only. In 2006, Ahmed changed the pageant name to Miss Pakistan World, and carried on the pageant internationally and hence established the first official pageant for Pakistan. Ahmed consider's these events as a sort of civil rights<ref name=\"indianexpress.com\"/> movements,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dnaindia.com/world/report_pakistani-canadian-kills-daughter-over-hijab_1138800|title=Pakistani Canadian kills daughter over hijab|work=dna|accessdate=15 November 2014}}</ref><ref>[http://www.dailymailnews.com/0908/20/ShowBiz/ShowBiz1.php]  {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091209190509/http://www.dailymailnews.com/0908/20/ShowBiz/ShowBiz1.php |date=December 9, 2009 }}</ref> through which it is hoped that the young and married women of Pakistan are able to gain a voice on the international stage.<ref name=\"tribuneindia.com\">{{cite web|url=http://www.tribuneindia.com/2011/20111205/ttlife1.htm|title=The Tribune, Chandigarh, India - The Tribune Lifestyle|publisher=Tribuneindia.com|accessdate=15 November 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.desixpress.co.uk/article.aspx?articleId=176|title=Desixpress.co.uk - No .1 For Asian Entertainment|publisher=Tribuneindia.com|accessdate=15 November 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141129025316/http://www.desixpress.co.uk/article.aspx?articleId=176|archive-date=29 November 2014|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n===Mrs. Pakistan World===\nIn 2007, Ahmed established the Mrs. Pakistan World<ref>[http://finance.alphatrade.com/story/2013-02-14/CNW/201302141718CANADANWCANADAPR_C5856.html] {{dead link|date=November 2014}}</ref> pageant for married Pakistani women from around the world. Winners were crowned from countries like USA, Canada and Norway. It was unimaginable for married Pakistani women to be seen in beauty pageants, and Ahmed made sure that married women<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.newswire.ca/en/story/1114989/pakistan-gets-its-mrs-pakistan-world-2013-farah-mahmood|title=Farah mahmood - Pakistan gets its Mrs. Pakistan World 2013 - Farah Mahmood|publisher=Newswire.ca|accessdate=15 November 2014}}</ref> of Pakistani descent were given an opportunity. Though the pageant was small, it did not go unnoticed, and took part in major international pageants like Mrs. World, [[Mrs. Universe]] and Mrs. Earth.\n\n===Mr. Pakistan World===\nIn 2011, Ahmed went ahead with the Mr. Pakistan World<ref>https://tribune.com.pk/story/1572317/4-pakistan-shines-mr-ocean-2017/</ref> event, a male competition for Pakistan to generate more youth to participate in areas where a lighter side of Pakistan could be shown.\n\nAfter the inclusion of the Mr. Pakistan World competition, the community participation increased with less resistance. [[Pakistan]]'s entertainment industry began changing as well and hence there was more stability in the acceptance of beauty pageants by Pakistan. This led to more scope for the competition out of Canada. In 2014, Ahmed moved the Miss Pakistan World and Mr. Pakistan World pageant to the United States<ref>{{cite web|url=http://thealternativepress.com/articles/2014-miss-pakistan-world-pageant-coming-to-edison|title=2014 Miss Pakistan World Pageant Coming to Edison|work=The Alternative Press|accessdate=15 November 2014}}</ref> and the 12th Miss Pakistan World and 4th Mr. Pakistan World took place in [[New Jersey]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.my9nj.com/story/26474107/2014-miss-pakistan-world-pageant-coming-to-edison |access-date=October 30, 2014 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141010080437/http://www.my9nj.com/story/26474107/2014-miss-pakistan-world-pageant-coming-to-edison |archive-date=October 10, 2014 }}</ref> USA. \n\n===Miss Pakistan===\nIn 2016, Ahmed got successful sending her first delegates directly from [[Pakistan]] to represent Pakistan in international pageants. Diya Ali<ref>https://tribune.com.pk/story/1648074/4-lahore-based-diya-ali-participate-miss-eco-international-2018/</ref> was the first representative from Pakistan<ref>https://images.dawn.com/news/1176877</ref> in 2016, and won the Miss Perpetual<ref>http://tribune.com.pk/story/1281667/pakistani-model-aiming-miss-world-title/</ref> title in [[Manila]], [[Philippines]] at the [[Miss Asia Pacific International]] pageant.\n\n===Director/Producer===\nIn 2014, Ahmed filmed her first documentary, \"[[I Shall Dance]],<ref name=\"enewspak.com\">[https://archive.is/20140707112313/http://enewspak.com/i-shall-dance-a-film-by-sonia-ahmed/]</ref><ref name=\"imdb.com\">{{cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt3776294|title=I Shall Dance (2014)|work=IMDb|accessdate=15 November 2014}}</ref>\" under her production company, Touchgate Global Inc., which released in September 2014{{Update after|2015|2|6}} in Toronto, Ontario, Canada.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://enewspak.com/i-shall-dance-a-documentary-on-dance-in-the-islamic-republic-of-pakistan/ |access-date=July 7, 2014 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140714213723/http://enewspak.com/i-shall-dance-a-documentary-on-dance-in-the-islamic-republic-of-pakistan/ |archive-date=July 14, 2014 }}</ref>\n\nIn 2016 Ahmed started her [[Lollywood]]<ref>http://images.dawn.com/news/1176095</ref> film production under her company Touchgate Global Inc. in Toronto, Ontario, Canada.<ref name=\"images.dawn.com\">http://images.dawn.com/news/1176154/mikaal-zulfiqar-and-ali-kazmi-to-star-in-a-desi-comedy-in-canada</ref> The name of the movie is \"[[Na Band Na Baraati]],\" starring [[Qavi Khan]], Azra Mohyeddin, [[Atiqa Odho]], [[Ali Kazmi]], [[Anzhelika Tahir]]<ref>https://tribune.com.pk/story/1302679/new-kids-block/</ref> and [[Mikaal Zulfiqar]] but has been unaccredited for it.\n\n==Filmography==\n{|class=\"wikitable\" style=\"font-size: 95%;\"\n|-\n! style=\"background:#B0C4DE;\" | Year\n! style=\"background:#B0C4DE;\" | Film\n! style=\"background:#B0C4DE;\" | Role\n! style=\"background:#B0C4DE;\" | Language\n! style=\"background:#B0C4DE;\" | Notes\n|-\n| 2020\n| ''TBA''\n|Director/Producer\n| Urdu\n|Filming \n|-\n| 2016\n| ''[[Na Band Na Baraati]]''<ref name=\"images.dawn.com\"/>\n|Director/Producer\n| Urdu\n|Unaccredited \n|-\n| 2014\n| ''[[I Shall Dance]]<ref name=\"enewspak.com\"/><ref name=\"imdb.com\"/>''\n|Director/Producer/Writer\n| Urdu/English\n|Ahmed's first documentary feature film\n|}\n\n==Other works==\nAhmed has been active part of charities around the world. In November 2011, Ahmed was invited to India,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://pakistanexaminer.com/?p=8784|title=HugeDomains.com - PakistanExaminer.com is for Sale (Pakistan Examiner)|publisher=Pakistanexaminer.com|accessdate=15 November 2014}}</ref> where she took part in various schools in regards to speaking<ref>{{cite web|url=http://solgens.us/india/bharatsandesh/newsdetail.php?n_id=712 |access-date=December 15, 2011 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120426052221/http://solgens.us/india/bharatsandesh/newsdetail.php?n_id=712 |archive-date=April 26, 2012 }}</ref> on India Pakistan relations<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tribuneindia.com/2011/20111209/cth1.htm#17|title=The Tribune, Chandigarh, India - Chandigarh Stories|publisher=Tribuneindia.com|accessdate=15 November 2014}}</ref> and on women's issues.<ref name=\"newseastwest.com\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.indianewscalling.com/tip.php?tipid=18124 |access-date=December 15, 2011 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120406072119/http://www.indianewscalling.com/tip.php?tipid=18124 |archive-date=April 6, 2012 }}</ref> Ahmed has also been an avid supporter of President [[Pervez Musharraf]] and has always shown her appreciation in the media.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.indianexpress.com/news/-i-love-you-musharraf-and-will-always-do-/523026/0|title=I love you Musharraf and will always do|publisher=Indianexpress.com|accessdate=15 November 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.southasianobserver.com/topstories.php?cid=1030|title=South Asian Observer - Top Story Indian Girl Wins Spelling Bee Contest In Ghana|publisher=Southasianobserver.com|access-date=15 November 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141128180005/http://www.southasianobserver.com/topstories.php?cid=1030|archive-date=2014-11-28|url-status=dead|df=}}</ref> Since 2012, Ahmed has started writing for publications in Canada<ref name=\"newseastwest.com\">{{cite web|url=http://newseastwest.com/why-india-and-pakistan-cannot-live-like-canada-and-us-and-call-themselves-hinpak-or-pakind-asks-miss-pakistan-world-boss-sonia-ahmed/|title=Why India and Pakistan cannot live like Canada and US, and call themselves 'HinPak' or 'Pakind,' asks Miss Pakistan World boss Sonia Ahmed|publisher=Newseastwest.com|access-date=15 November 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141129022744/http://newseastwest.com/why-india-and-pakistan-cannot-live-like-canada-and-us-and-call-themselves-hinpak-or-pakind-asks-miss-pakistan-world-boss-sonia-ahmed/|archive-date=2014-11-29|url-status=dead|df=}}</ref> and India<ref>{{cite web|url=http://newseastwest.com/miss-pakistan-pageant-founder-sonia-ahmed-on-why-musharraf-is-facing-all-these-problems-in-pakistan-today/|title=Miss Pakistan pageant founder Sonia Ahmed on why Musharraf is facing all these problems in Pakistan today|publisher=Newseastwest.com|accessdate=15 November 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://newseastwest.com/mistreatment-of-pakistani-artists-bothers-me/|title=Mistreatment of artists in Pakistan bothers me|publisher=Newseastwest.com|access-date=15 November 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141129022750/http://newseastwest.com/mistreatment-of-pakistani-artists-bothers-me/|archive-date=2014-11-29|url-status=dead|df=}}</ref>\n\n==Controversies==\n\nIn 2003,<ref name=\"Tehelka.com\">{{cite web|url=http://www.tehelka.com/story_main52.asp?filename=hub100312Neighbour.asp|title=Tehelka - India's Independent Weekly News Magazine|publisher=Tehelka.com|accessdate=15 November 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121014192605/http://www.tehelka.com/story_main52.asp?filename=hub100312Neighbour.asp|archive-date=14 October 2012|url-status=dead}}</ref> Ahmed<ref>http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/delhi-times/agents-of-change-or-miss-representations/articleshow/1973519.cms</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hindustantimes.com/Entertainment/Fashion/Miss-Pakistan-comes-to-India/Article1-803738.aspx|title=Miss Pakistan Comes To India|publisher=Hindustantimes.com|accessdate=15 November 2014}}</ref> was facing issues<ref name=\"tribuneindia.com\"/> with holding the pageant as some conservative sections<ref name=\"ryerson\"/> of the community were against the existence of Miss Pakistan World. As time went on, the controversies fizzled out.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.theasiantoday.com/article.aspx?articleId=176|title=Crowning glory for 'Miss Pakistan' beauty pageants|access-date=15 November 2014|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141129041140/http://www.theasiantoday.com/article.aspx?articleId=176|archive-date=29 November 2014|df=}}</ref> Moreover, Ahmed, was in the news several times expressing her likeness for the then President of Pakistan, [[Pervez Musharraf]].<ref>http://archive.indianexpress.com/news/-i-love-you-musharraf-and-will-always-do-/523026/</ref> Ahmed maintains that she is a hard core fan till to date.\n\nIn August 2010, Ahmed was criticized<ref name=\"Guardian\"/> for going ahead with the 8th annual Miss Pakistan World,<ref name= \"Guardian\">{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2010/aug/19/pakistan-anger-beauty-contest-floods|title=Miss Pakistan World pageant's timing causes dismay|work=the Guardian|accessdate=15 November 2014}}</ref><ref name= \"Toronto Star\">{{cite web|url=https://www.thestar.com/news/gta/article/850312--pakistani-beauty-pageant-to-go-ahead|title=Pakistani beauty pageant to go ahead|work=thestar.com|accessdate=15 November 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.care2.com/causes/human-rights/blog/is-a-miss-pakistan-pageant-appropriate-right-now/|title=Is a Miss Pakistan Pageant Appropriate Right Now?|publisher=Care2.com|accessdate=15 November 2014}}</ref> when Pakistan was hit with floods 3 weeks prior to the actual event.<ref name= \"Globe & Mail\">{{cite web|url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/news/national/toronto/organizers-criticized-for-running-pakistani-pageant-in-wake-of-flood-disaster/article1679280/|title=Organizers criticized for running Pakistani pageant in wake of flood disaster|work=The Globe and Mail|accessdate=15 November 2014}}</ref><ref>[http://www.torontosun.com/blogs/themotts/2010/08/23/15115626.html] {{dead link|date=November 2014}}</ref> Ahmed stood her grounds<ref name=\"Toronto Star\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://blogs.canoe.ca/themotts/disaster/few-flood-to-miss-pakistan/|title=Few Flood to Miss Pakistan|author=|work=The Motts Sound Off|access-date=15 November 2014|archive-url=https://archive.is/20120711224801/http://blogs.canoe.ca/themotts/disaster/few-flood-to-miss-pakistan/|archive-date=2012-07-11|url-status=dead|df=}}</ref> and said that the plans for holding the event would go on regardless. The other controversy surrounding the event was that it was held in the month of Ramadan. In an interview, Ahmed stated that the event was held after the fasting hours, and that Ramadan is a celebration not a mourning period. Ahmed has also always spoken very openly about her opponents who were mainly the conservative Pakistani community around the world.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://newseastwest.com/give-up-miss-pakistan-pageant-president-sonia-ahmed-tells-her-opponents/|archive-url=https://archive.is/20130130072314/http://newseastwest.com/give-up-miss-pakistan-pageant-president-sonia-ahmed-tells-her-opponents/|url-status=dead|archive-date=30 January 2013|title=Miss Pakistan World president Sonia Ahmed slams her opponents|publisher=Newseastwest.com|access-date=15 November 2014}}</ref> Ahmed<ref name=\"Tehelka.com\"/> has also backed controversial<ref>{{cite web|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/videos/celebs/Miss-Pak-World-president-backs-Veena-Malik/videoshow/11047751.cms |access-date=January 21, 2012 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120112114514/http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/videos/celebs/Miss-Pak-World-President-backs-Veena-Malik/videoshow/11047751.cms |archive-date=January 12, 2012 }}</ref> Pakistani actress [[Veena Malik]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.firstpost.com/printpage.php?idno=155625&sr_no=0|title=Print :Where's the fatwa? Veena Malik strips, Pakistan yawns|publisher=Firstpost.com|access-date=15 November 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150619234239/http://www.firstpost.com/printpage.php?idno=155625&sr_no=0|archive-date=2015-06-19|url-status=dead|df=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.indiablooms.com/EntVideo2Details/entPVVideoDetails091211l1.php|title=Miss Pak World prez backs Veena Malik|publisher=Indiablooms.com|access-date=15 November 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141109120850/http://www.indiablooms.com/EntVideo2Details/entPVVideoDetails091211l1.php|archive-date=2014-11-09|url-status=dead|df=}}</ref> on cover shoot for an Indian magazine FHM.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://video.in.msn.com/watch/video/miss-pak-world-prez-backs-veena/fdh5k7pk|title=Video - msn|publisher=Video.in.msn.com|accessdate=15 November 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120108123950/http://video.in.msn.com/watch/video/miss-pak-world-prez-backs-veena/fdh5k7pk|archive-date=8 January 2012|url-status=dead}}</ref> Ahmed also came on Indian live news channels, Tez Khabarain and [[Aaj Tak]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://aajtak.intoday.in/video/Veena-Malik-to-marry-on-TV-for-1.5-crore-1-686405.html|title=\u0935\u0940\u0928\u093e \u0915\u0947 \u0938\u094d\u200d\u0935\u092f\u0902\u0935\u0930 \u092a\u0930 \u0926\u094b \u0926\u0947\u0936\u094b\u0902 \u092e\u0947\u0902 \u092c\u0930\u092a\u093e \u0939\u0902\u0917\u093e\u092e\u093e \u0964 \u0939\u0938\u0940\u0928\u093e\u0913\u0902 \u0915\u093e \u091c\u0932\u0935\u093e \u0914\u0930 \u092d\u0940|publisher=Aajtak.intoday.in|accessdate=15 November 2014}}</ref> and defended Malik, against a local [[Mufti]], actress [[Dolly Bindra]] and actor [[Raza Murad]].\n\nOn December 5, 2019, Ahmed<ref>https://people.com/human-interest/former-miss-pakistan-world-zanib-naveed-dies-car-crash/</ref> was interviewed by [[People (magazine)]] [[Los Angeles]] [[United States]] for the untimely death of one of the winners of [[Miss Pakistan World]] [[Zanib Naveed]]. Ahmed answered, \u201cAs the President of Miss Pakistan World, we gave Naveed an amazing platform to represent Pakistan internationally and hearing about her death is very upsetting to all of us,\u201d Ahmed said. \u201cBeing a beauty queen to a country like Pakistan where there have been no beauty pageants on the soil of Pakistan is a tough job!\u201d \u201cNaveed along with other winners of Miss Pakistan World had a huge responsibility of carrying the title of a Muslim Nation,\u201d she continued. \u201cIt is a very upsetting time and terrible news and we can all hope and pray that her family gets through this painful situation.\u201d\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb name|6381973}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20120108123950/http://video.in.msn.com/watch/video/miss-pak-world-prez-backs-veena/fdh5k7pk ANI Interview]\n* [http://www.soniaahmedofficial.com/ Official Sonia Ahmed Site]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20110606012613/http://www.diversitywatch.ryerson.ca/media/cache/pakistanipageant_star_mar14.htm Toronto Star Article ]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Ahmed, Sonia}}\n[[Category:Canadian businesspeople of Pakistani descent]]\n[[Category:1980 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Pakistani Sunni Muslims]]\n[[Category:Pakistani women]]\n[[Category:Punjabi women]]\n[[Category:Businesspeople from Karachi]]\n[[Category:Businesspeople from Ottawa]]\n[[Category:Businesspeople from Toronto]]\n[[Category:Canadian people of Pakistani descent]]\n[[Category:Pakistani expatriates in Kuwait]]\n[[Category:University of Ottawa alumni]]\n", "name_user": "Salut65", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sonia_Ahmed"}
{"title_page": "Brian Dennehy", "text_new": "{{recentdeath}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{short description|American actor}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Brian Dennehy\n| image              = BrianDennehyJul2009.jpg\n| alt                =\n| caption            = Dennehy in 2009\n| birth_name         = Brian Manion Dennehy\n| birth_date         = {{birth date|1938|7|9}}\n| birth_place        = [[Bridgeport, Connecticut]], U.S.\n| death_date         = {{death date and age|2020|4|15|1938|7|9}}\n| death_place        = [[New Haven, Connecticut]], U.S.\n| occupation         = Actor\n| years_active       = 1965\u20132020\n| spouse             = {{marriage|Judith Scheff|1959|1974}}<br />{{marriage|Jennifer Arnott|1988}}\n| children           = 5; including [[Elizabeth Dennehy]]\n| website            =\n}}\n'''Brian Manion Dennehy''' (July 9, 1938 \u2013 April 15, 2020) was an American actor of film, stage, and television. A winner of one [[Golden Globe]], two [[Tony Awards]] and a recipient of six [[Primetime Emmy Award]] nominations, he gained initial recognition in film for his role as Sheriff Will Teasle in ''[[First Blood]]'' (1982). He had roles in numerous films including ''[[Gorky Park (film)|Gorky Park]]'' (1983), ''[[Silverado (film)|Silverado]]'' (1985), ''[[Cocoon (film)|Cocoon]]'' (1985), ''[[F/X]]'' (1986), ''[[Presumed Innocent (film)|Presumed Innocent]]'' (1990), ''[[Romeo + Juliet]]'' (1996), and ''[[Knight of Cups (film)|Knight of Cups]]'' (2015). Dennehy won the [[Golden Globe Award for Best Actor \u2013 Miniseries or Television Film|Golden Globe Award for Best Actor in a Miniseries or Television Film]] for his role as [[Willy Loman]] in the television film ''[[Death of a Salesman (2000 film)|Death of a Salesman]]'' (2000).\n\nAccording to ''[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]'', Dennehy was \"perhaps the foremost living interpreter\" of playwright [[Eugene O'Neill]]\u2019s works on stage and screen. He had a decades long relationship with Chicago's [[Goodman Theatre]] where much of his O'Neill work originated.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Dagan |first=Carmel |url=https://variety.com/2020/film/news/brian-dennehy-dead-dies-tommy-boy-first-blood-1234582309/ |title=Brian Dennehy, \u2018Tommy Boy\u2019 and \u2018First Blood\u2019 Star, Dies at 81 |date=2020-04-16 |work=Variety |access-date=2020-04-16 |language=en}}</ref> He also regularly played Canada's [[Stratford Festival]], especially in works by [[William Shakespeare]] and [[Samuel Beckett]]. He once gave credit for his award-winning performances to the play's authors: \"When you walk with giants, you learn how to take bigger steps.\"<ref name=star2008>{{cite news | access-date = April 17, 2020 | work = Toronto Star | first = Richard | last = Ouzonian | url = https://www.thestar.com/entertainment/stage/2008/06/21/life_of_brian.html |date=June 21, 2008 | title = Life of Brian }}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nBrian Manion Dennehy<ref name=nytobit/> was born on July 9, 1938 in [[Bridgeport, Connecticut]], the son of Hannah (Manion) and Edward Dennehy, a [[News agency|wire service]] editor for the [[Associated Press]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.northjersey.com/community-news/grateful-that-my-parents-came-to-america-1.906633|title = Grateful that my parents came to America|author=Dennehy, Michael|work=NorthJersey.com}}</ref> He had two brothers, Michael and Edward.<ref name=filmreference>{{cite web | author= | title=Brian Dennehy Biography | url=http://www.filmreference.com/film/48/Brian-Dennehy.html | work=filmreference | year=2008 | accessdate=April 10, 2008}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | author= | title=Brian Dennehy Biography | url=https://movies.yahoo.com/movie/contributor/1800026870/bio | work=Yahoo! Movies | year=2008 | accessdate=April 10, 2008}}</ref> He was of [[Irish people|Irish]] ancestry and was raised [[Catholic Church|Catholic]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Parsi|first=Novid|url=http://chicago.timeout.com/articles/theater/81821/brian-dennehy-interview|title=Dennehy's Last Tape|work=[[Time Out Group|Time Out]]|quote = I come from an Irish Catholic family,...|date=January 7, 2010|accessdate=June 24, 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Harmetz|first=Aljean|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1989/04/23/movies/film-for-brian-dennehy-character-tells-all.html?pagewanted=all|title=FILM; For Brian Dennehy, Character Tells All|work=[[The New York Times]]|date=April 23, 1989|accessdate=June 24, 2010}}</ref> The family relocated to [[Long Island, New York]], where Dennehy attended [[Chaminade High School]] in the village of [[Mineola, New York|Mineola]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Guzm\u00e1n |first=Rafer |date=February 14, 2013 |title=Brian Dennehy returns to Long Island |url=https://www.newsday.com/entertainment/celebrities/brian-dennehy-returns-to-long-island-1.4642522 |work=[[Newsday]] |access-date=March 17, 2018}}</ref>\n\nA football scholarship paved the way to [[Columbia University]] in New York City, where he played [[American football|football]], earned a B.A. in history, became a member of the [[Sigma Chi]] fraternity and played [[rugby union]] for [[Old Blue R.F.C.]] Prior to pursuing acting Dennehy worked as a stockbroker for Merrill Lynch in their Manhattan office in the mid 1970s.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.college.columbia.edu/cct_archive/spr99/12a_fr.html|title = Death of a Salesman, Birth of a Star | access-date = April 16, 2020 | first = Shira J. | last = Boss |work = Colombia College Today | date = Spring 1999 }}</ref>\n\n==Career==\n{{Refimprove|section|date=April 2020}}\n===Film===\nDennehy was primarily known as a dramatic actor. His breakthrough role was as the overzealous [[sheriff]] Will Teasle in ''[[First Blood]]'' (1982) opposite [[Sylvester Stallone]] as [[John Rambo]].\n\nHis earlier films included several comedies, like ''[[Semi-Tough]]'' with [[Burt Reynolds]] (in which he portrayed a pro football player), ''[[Foul Play (1978 film)|Foul Play]]'' with [[Chevy Chase]], and ''[[10 (film)|10]]'' with [[Dudley Moore]] (as a [[Manzanillo, Colima|Manzanillo]] bartender). He later portrayed a corrupt sheriff in the western ''[[Silverado (film)|Silverado]]'' and an [[Extraterrestrial life|alien]] in ''[[Cocoon (film)|Cocoon]]'', both released in 1985.\n\nMemorable supporting parts featured Dennehy in such films as ''[[Split Image (film)|Split Image]]'' (1982), ''[[Legal Eagles]]'' (1986), ''[[F/X]]: Murder By Illusion'' (1986), ''[[Presumed Innocent (film)|Presumed Innocent]]'' (1990), ''[[F/X2]]: The Deadly Art of Illusion'' (1991) and Prophet of Evil (1993)\n\nDennehy gradually became a valuable [[character actor]] but also achieved leading-man status in the thriller ''[[Best Seller]]'' (1987) co-starring [[James Woods]]. He also starred in the [[Peter Greenaway]] film ''[[The Belly of an Architect]]'', for which he won the Best Actor Award at the 1987 [[Chicago International Film Festival]]. Commenting upon this unusual venture, Dennehy said, \"I've been in a lot of movies but this is the first film I've made.\"\n\nHe went on to star as Harrison in the Australian film ''[[The Man from Snowy River II]]'' in 1988.\n\nOne of his most well-known roles came in the 1995 [[Chris Farley]]-[[David Spade]] comedy ''[[Tommy Boy (film)|Tommy Boy]]'' as Big Tom Callahan. He also was reunited with his ''10'' co-star [[Bo Derek]] in ''Tommy Boy'', in which she played his wife.\n\nDennehy had a voice role in the animated movie ''[[Ratatouille (film)|Ratatouille]]'' as Django, father of the rat chef Remy. He appeared as the superior officer of [[Robert De Niro]] and [[Al Pacino]] in the 2008 cop drama ''[[Righteous Kill]]'' and as the father of [[Russell Crowe]] in the 2010 suspense film ''[[The Next Three Days]]''.\n\nDennehy starred as [[Clarence Darrow]] in ''[[Alleged (film)|Alleged]]'', a film based on the [[Scopes Monkey Trial]], the famous court battle over the teaching of evolution in American public schools.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mlive.com/news/flint/2009/08/brian_dennehy_fred_thompson_to.html|title=Brian Dennehy, Fred Thompson to star in film shooting at Crossroads Village|first=Liz Shaw &#124; Flint|last=Journal|date=August 29, 2009|website=mlive}}</ref>\n\n===Television {{anchor|TV}}===\nDennehy began his professional acting career in small guest roles in such 1970s and 1980s series as ''[[Kojak]]'', ''[[Lou Grant (TV series)|Lou Grant]]'', ''[[Dallas (1978 TV series)|Dallas]]'', ''[[Dynasty (1981 TV series)|Dynasty]]'', and ''[[Hunter (1984 American TV series)|Hunter]]''. He also appeared in an episode of ''[[Miami Vice]]'' during the 1987\u201388 season.\n\n[[File:Brian Dennehy DF-SD-05-12671.jpg|thumb|left|Dennehy in 2003]]\nDennehy portrayed Sergeant Ned T. \"Frozen Chosen\" Coleman in the television movie ''[[A Rumor of War (miniseries)|A Rumor of War]]'' (1980) opposite [[Brad Davis (actor)|Brad Davis]]. He continued to appear in such high-profile television films as ''[[Skokie (film)|Skokie]]'' (1981), ''[[Split Image (film)|Split Image]]'' (1982), ''[[Day One (1989 film)|Day One]]'' (1989), ''[[A Killing in a Small Town]]'' (1990) opposite [[Barbara Hershey]]. He also played the title role in [[HBO]]'s ''[[Teamster Boss: The Jackie Presser Story]]''.\n\nDennehy had a lead role as [[fire chief]]/celebrity dad Leslie \"Buddy\" Krebs in the short-lived 1982 series ''[[Star of the Family]]''. Despite his star power, that show was canceled after a half a season.\n\nDennehy was nominated for [[Emmy Awards]] six times for his television movies. In 1992, he was nominated for Outstanding Lead Actor in a Miniseries or TV Movie for his performance as [[John Wayne Gacy]] in ''[[To Catch a Killer]]'', and was nominated that same year in a different category, Outstanding Supporting Actor in a Miniseries or TV Movie, for ''The Burden of Proof''. Other Emmy nominations were for his work in ''A Killing in a Small Town'', ''[[Murder in the Heartland]]'' (1993) and for the [[Showtime (TV network)|Showtime]] cable TV movie ''Our Fathers'' (2005), which was about the [[Roman Catholic Church sex abuse scandal]]. In 2000, Dennehy was nominated for an Emmy for Outstanding Lead Actor in a Miniseries or TV Movie for a television presentation of his performance as [[Willy Loman]] in [[Arthur Miller]]'s ''[[Death of a Salesman]]'' which he had performed on [[Broadway theatre|Broadway]]. The performance did, however, precipitate a [[Golden Globe Award]].\n\nHe starred in the popular crime drama ''[[Jack Reed (series)|Jack Reed]]'' TV movies. He also appeared as a recurring character in the [[NBC]] sitcom ''[[Just Shoot Me!]]''.\n\nA cartoon version of Dennehy appeared in the film ''[[South Park: Bigger, Longer & Uncut]]'' (1999) and an episode of ''[[The Simpsons]]''.\n\nIn January 2007, he starred in the episode \"[[Law & Order: Special Victims Unit (season 8)|Scheherazade]]\" of ''[[Law & Order: Special Victims Unit]]'' as a retired criminal who wants to reconnect with his daughter and admit his crimes before dying of a terminal disease thus eventually clearing a wrongfully imprisoned inmate. In April 2008, Dennehy guest-starred as a [[Teamster]] boss in [[Sandwich Day|an episode]] of ''[[30 Rock]]''.\n\nDennehy guest-starred in a 2009 episode of ''[[Rules of Engagement (TV series)|Rules of Engagement]]'' as the father of the main character, Jeff.<ref>{{cite web|title=Exclusive: Brian Dennehy Lands \"Meaty\" Sitcom Role |url=http://community.tvguide.com/blog-entry/TVGuide-News-Blog/Todays-News/Exclusive-Brian-Dennehy/800046124 |work=[[TV Guide]] |year=2008 |accessdate=September 4, 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080906220125/http://community.tvguide.com/blog-entry/TVGuide-News-Blog/Todays-News/Exclusive-Brian-Dennehy/800046124 |archivedate=September 6, 2008 }}</ref>\n\nDennehy also narrated many television programs.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/name/nm0001133/|title=Brian Dennehy's IMDB profile|accessdate=March 20, 2009}}</ref> He narrated Canadian-Irish docudrama ''[[Death or Canada]]''.<ref>{{cite news| url = http://www.rte.ie/arts/2009/0108/ifta.html|title = IFTA nominations for Farrell & Gleeson |date = January 8, 2009|accessdate=January 8, 2009|publisher=[[Raidi\u00f3 Teilif\u00eds \u00c9ireann|RT\u00c9]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite news| url = https://www.thestar.com/Entertainment/article/601265|title=Brian Dennehy narrates film on Toronto's role in Irish famine| date = March 12, 2009|accessdate=March 20, 2009 | work=The Star | first=Victoria | last=Ahearn}}</ref>\n\nDennehy was set to star in the [[Amazon Studios]] series ''Cocked'' which will co-star [[Jason Lee (actor)|Jason Lee]], [[Dreama Walker]], [[Diora Baird]], and [[Sam Trammell]].\n\nDennehy starred as Elizabeth Keen's grandfather on the NBC series ''[[The Blacklist (TV series)|The Blacklist]]''.\n\n===Theater===\nDennehy won two [[Tony Awards]], both times for Best Lead Actor in a Play. The first win was for ''[[Death of a Salesman]]'' (for which he also won a [[Laurence Olivier Award]] for the production's London run), in 1999, and the second was for [[Eugene O'Neill]]'s ''[[Long Day's Journey into Night]]'' in 2003. Both productions were directed by [[Robert Falls]] and were originally produced at the [[Goodman Theatre]] company in [[Chicago]].\n\nOn stage, Dennehy made frequent performances in the Chicago theater world, and made his Broadway debut in 1995 in [[Brian Friel]]'s ''[[Translations]]''. In 1999, he was the first male performer to be voted the [[Sarah Siddons Award]] for his work in [[Theatre in Chicago|Chicago theater]]. He made a return to Broadway in 2007 as Matthew Harrison Brady in ''[[Inherit the Wind (play)|Inherit the Wind]]'' opposite [[Christopher Plummer]], then returned again opposite [[Carla Gugino]] in a 2009 revival of [[Eugene O'Neill]]'s [[Desire Under the Elms]].\n\nIn fall 1992, he played the lead role of Hickey in Robert Falls's production of [[Eugene O'Neill]]'s ''[[The Iceman Cometh]]'' at the [[Abbey Theatre]] in Dublin.<ref name=\"irishtimes-bull\" />\n\nIn 2008, Dennehy appeared at the [[Stratford Shakespeare Festival]], in Stratford, Ontario, Canada, appearing in ''[[All's Well That Ends Well]]'' as the King of France,<ref name=star2008/> and a double bill of plays, [[Samuel Beckett]]'s ''[[Krapp's Last Tape]]'' and Eugene O'Neill's ''[[Hughie]]'', where Dennehy reprised the role of Erie Smith.<ref>{{cite news | access-date = April 17, 2020 | url = https://www.thestar.com/entertainment/2008/06/30/hughie_krapps_last_tape_dennehy_dazzles.html | first = Richard | last = Ouzonian | work = Toronto Star | date = June 30, 2008 | title = Hughie Krapp's Last Tape: Dennehy dazzles }}</ref>\n\nIn 2010, he was inducted into the [[American Theatre Hall of Fame]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.playbill.com/news/article/146911-Theater-Hall-of-Fame-Ceremony-Honoring-Linda-Lavin-Brian-Dennehy-Michael-Blakemore-Presented-Jan-24 |title=Theater Hall of Fame Ceremony, Honoring Linda Lavin, Brian Dennehy, Michael Blakemore, Presented Jan. 24 |work=Playbill |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140222204659/http://www.playbill.com/news/article/146911-Theater-Hall-of-Fame-Ceremony-Honoring-Linda-Lavin-Brian-Dennehy-Michael-Blakemore-Presented-Jan-24 |archivedate=February 22, 2014 }}</ref>\n\nIn December 2010, he returned to Ireland to play Bull McCabe in the [[Olympia Theatre (Dublin)|Olympia Theatre]] of [[Dublin]]'s stage version of [[John B. Keane]]'s ''[[The Field (play)|The Field]]''.<ref name=\"irishtimes-bull\">\n{{Cite news|url=http://www.irishtimes.com/newspaper/weekend/2011/0108/1224287012018.html|title=The Bull in winter|publisher=The Irish Times | date=January 1, 2011}}\n</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.irishtimes.com/newspaper/weekend/2011/0122/1224288049876.html|title=Real-life dramas? We don't do those. But John B Keane did|author=Fintan O'Toole|publisher=The Irish Times|date=January 1, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.independent.ie/entertainment/arts/the-ignoble-passions-of-the-field-fail-to-ignite-2507559.html|title=The ignoble passions of The Field fail to ignite|author=Emer O'Kelly|publisher=Independent.ie|date=January 23, 2011}}</ref>\n\nIn 2011, Dennehy returned to the [[Stratford Shakespeare Festival]] in the role of Sir Toby Belch in Shakespeare's ''[[Twelfth Night]]''. He also played Max in [[Harold Pinter]]'s ''[[The Homecoming]]'', the first Pinter work to be produced there.<ref>{{cite news | work = New York Times | access-date = April 16, 2020 | url = https://www.nytimes.com/2011/09/03/theater/brian-dennehy-at-stratford-shakespeare-festival.html | date = September 2, 2011 | title = Brian Dennehy as a Troublemaker, Times Two | first = Charles | last = Isherwood}}</ref>\n\nIn April through June 2012, he played the role of Larry Slade in the [[Eugene O'Neill]] play ''[[The Iceman Cometh]]'' at the [[Goodman Theatre]] in Chicago,<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/robert-bullen/iceman-cometh-play_b_1484561.html | work=Huffington Post | first=Robert | last=Bullen | title=Goodman's Iceman Cometh, Starring Nathan Lane, Chills to the Core | date=May 8, 2012}}</ref> which he reprised in 2015 when the production, with most of the Goodman Theater production cast, was revived at the BAM Harvey Theater in Brooklyn, New York.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/02/13/theater/review-the-iceman-cometh-revived-with-nathan-lane-and-brian-dennehy.html?_r=0 | work=New York Times | first=Charles | last=Isherwood | title=Review: 'The Iceman Cometh' Revived, With Nathan Lane and Brian Dennehy | date=February 12, 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life and death==\nDennehy enlisted in the [[United States Marine Corps]] from 1958 to 1963, including a brief stint on [[Okinawa]]. \n\nHe married twice and had five children including actress [[Elizabeth Dennehy]].<ref>{{cite web |date=July 10, 2012 |title=Where Are They Now? TNG Guest Star Elizabeth Dennehy |publisher=StarTrek.com |url=http://www.startrek.com/article/where-are-they-now-tng-guest-star-elizabeth-dennehy |access-date=March 17, 2018}}</ref>\n\nDennehy died on April 15, 2020 of cardiac arrest due to sepsis during a hospital stay in [[New Haven, Connecticut]].<ref name=nytobit>{{cite news | url = https://www.nytimes.com/2020/04/16/movies/brian-dennehy-dead.html | title = Brian Dennehy Dies; Tony Award-Winning Actor Was 81 | first = Derrick Bryson | last = Taylor | work = New York Times | date = April 16, 2020 | access-date = April 16, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url = https://www.chicagotribune.com/entertainment/theater/chris-jones/ct-ent-actor-brian-dennehy-dies-0417-20200416-sftbe7dzurfmfk6zcq4yzrgvry-story.html | title = Brian Dennehy, a giant of Chicago and America\u2019s stages, is dead at 81 | first = Chris | last = Jones | work = Chicago Tribune | date = April 16, 2020 | access-date = April 16, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.registercitizen.com/news/article/Brian-Dennehy-Tony-winning-stage-screen-actor-15205508.php|title=Brian Dennehy, Tony-winning stage, screen actor, dies at 81|first1=Mark|last1=Kennedy|date=April 16, 2020|website=The Register Citizen}}</ref>\n\n==Filmography==\n===Film===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! class=\"unsortable\"| Notes\n|-\n| 1977\n| ''[[Looking for Mr. Goodbar (film)|Looking for Mr. Goodbar]]''\n| Surgeon\n|\n|-\n| 1977\n| ''[[Semi-Tough]]''\n| T.J. Lambert\n|\n|-\n| 1978\n| ''[[F.I.S.T.]]''\n| Frank Vasco\n|\n|-\n| 1978\n| ''[[Foul Play (1978 film)|Foul Play]]''\n| Fergie\n|\n|-\n| 1979\n| ''[[Butch and Sundance: The Early Days]]''\n| O.C. Hanks\n|\n|-\n| 1979\n| ''[[10 (film)|10]]''\n| Don the Bartender\n|\n|-\n| 1980\n| ''[[Little Miss Marker (1980 film)|Little Miss Marker]]''\n| Herbie\n|\n|-\n| 1982\n| ''[[Split Image (film)|Split Image]]''\n| Kevin Stetson\n|\n|-\n| 1982\n| ''[[First Blood]]''\n| Sheriff Will Teasle\n|\n|-\n| 1983\n| ''[[Never Cry Wolf (film)|Never Cry Wolf]]''\n| Rose Little\n|\n|-\n| 1983\n| ''[[Gorky Park (film